    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-01-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-01-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="751"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d751">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72114/3044</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        British Ambassador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRSCA1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Spring Rice</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d751fn1">A similar note was sent to the French
                        Ambassador on the same date. (File No. 872.48/149a.)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1457</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-01-05">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 5, 1918</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: Referring to the memorandum dated November
                    15, 1917,<note n="2" xml:id="d751fn2">Not printed.</note> of the British Embassy
                    and the Department’s reply thereto dated January 3, 1918,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d751fn3">Not printed.</note> concerning the provisioning of all
                    Serbian prisoners of war in enemy countries by the American National Red Cross,
                    I have the honor further to inform you that a credit will be extended to the
                    Serbian Government, and that the Red Cross is now ready to make purchases for
                    shipments of food for this purpose.</p>
                <p>Before making a final decision in this matter, however, I would be pleased to
                    have a definite expression of the views of the British Government that it
                    concurs in the proposed provisioning of all Serbian prisoners of war by the
                    American National Red Cross, and that the shipments of food to be sent to
                    Switzerland for distribution to the prisoners will be facilitated as much as
                    possible by His Majesty’s Government.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
